text: I think they're very much related things. Your valuation framework is going to drive your risk underwriting. I think one of the things that is important to me is that with our valuation and our underwriting approaches be relatively naive. You don't want to be too clever with it because the world might not work out the way that you thought it was going to. And so we try not to build too many things into this. One of the things that we do build into it is that these valuations are based on an earnings yield using a peak potential earnings yield. That's the maximum that we can possibly expect. But then on the other side, when we're underwriting these things, we're saying, hey, what happens if next week we are down in the left tail at a 95th, at a five percentile valuation and maybe a week from that, you're at a one percentile valuation. And I think for most of my clients, it's going to be a little bit of a different situation. I think for most of my career, people have thought that that was kind of silly. And then last year, it turned out that it was actually really useful because I knew exactly where we were. And as we were plumbing the depths, I knew exactly what we could do and what we should do. We didn't have that kind of paralysis of, hey, everything is changing. Everything is new. We kind of knew. And so what we do is we set these valuations where it's not just entirely like an earnings yield. There's another couple of components there, but that's the main value. And so what we do is we set these valuations where it's not just entirely like an earnings yield. There's another couple of components there, but that's the main value. And so what we do is we set these valuations where it's not just entirely like an earnings yield. There's another couple of components there, but that's the main value. And the earnings in this part essentially acts like a ratchet most part. It only really ratchets up unless we can get into this later because in the sector ones, it actually does drop. But at the macro level, it effectively doesn't really. I mean, it could, it just has never happened. And it wouldn't make sense unless we were experiencing extremely deflationary and this investment-oriented kind of scenario. And so what we're looking at here is saying, hey, historically, how cheap do these things get versus what their potential EPS is? And that doesn't really change. I mean, things really do kind of price to that potential forward. And during these liquidity crises, we get really deep into that left tail. And we didn't quite get there for large cap and mega cap last year because as they were starting to get into that freefall mode, we got the policy response. But in the mid cap space, in the small cap space, in the value, we definitely saw that happen. Depending on how you're segmenting the market and which cross sections you're looking at, a lot of these really did hit that one percentile valuation and these kind of valuations that we associated with the depths in both 2008 or 2009, depending on which sector we're talking about. And so that's kind of the core part. You look at these things and say, hey, the story looks good and the fundamentals look good. And maybe there's a lot of expectations, but then you go back. And you say, okay, well, let's take all of that away for a second. Let's see historically what we could expect to see in a left tail. And you start getting these kind of really scary numbers. You're starting to see for large cap growth right now, a full on tail scenario would be a 70% drawdown. I think most people really can't imagine that. But if you're invested in pretty generic, small and mid cap beta at the beginning of last year, you saw over the next, call it 10 weeks, you got there. You went from a pretty generic, probably 75 to 80th percentile valuation down to a one percentile.
